---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Sheet Tooltip"
  description="Custom sheet tooltip work for Amazon QuickSight visuals."
>
  <article class="p-6 lg:p-12 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <a
      href="/shipped"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-charcoal-muted dark:text-sand-muted
             hover:text-accent dark:hover:text-accent-light transition-colors mb-8"
    >
      <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M7 16l-4-4m0 0l4-4m-4 4h18" />
      </svg>
      Back to shipped work
    </a>

    <header class="mb-10">
      <div class="case-cover mb-8"><span>Cover image</span></div>
      <p class="text-sm text-accent dark:text-accent-light font-medium mb-4 tracking-wide uppercase">
        Amazon Web Services · QuickSight
      </p>
      <h1 class="font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-semibold text-balance leading-tight">Sheet Tooltip</h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal-muted dark:text-sand-muted">
        I worked on QuickSight sheet tooltip customization, enabling richer visual tooltips that can present more context directly inside dashboards.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/machine-learning/create-rich-custom-tooltips-in-amazon-quick-sight/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="btn btn-ghost border border-cream-300 dark:border-ink-lighter">Announcement post</a>
        <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/quick/latest/userguide/customizing-visual-tooltips.html#customizing-visual-tooltips-sheet" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="btn btn-ghost border border-cream-300 dark:border-ink-lighter">AWS docs</a>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>Problem</h2>
      <p>
        Dashboards often need more context than a default tooltip can provide. Authors need a way to
        expose supporting metrics, dimensions, and explanatory details without forcing readers to leave
        the visual they are inspecting.
      </p>

      <h2>What I Worked On</h2>
      <p>
        I contributed to sheet tooltip customization in Amazon QuickSight, which lets authors create richer
        tooltip experiences for visuals. The work fit into the dashboard authoring and reader experience,
        where tooltips need to feel responsive, predictable, and easy to understand.
      </p>

      <h2>Impact</h2>
      <p>
        Sheet tooltips help authors provide more useful context inside dashboards and give readers a clearer
        path from hovering over a visual to understanding the data behind it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .case-cover { display: grid; min-height: 18rem; place-items: center; border: 1px solid rgb(232 224 208); border-radius: 0.5rem; background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(47, 111, 159, 0.2) 25%, transparent 25%) 0 0 / 24px 24px, linear-gradient(135deg, transparent 75%, rgba(47, 111, 159, 0.16) 75%) 0 0 / 24px 24px, rgb(245 240 232); }
  :global(.dark) .case-cover { border-color: rgb(37 36 34); background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(59, 126, 161, 0.24) 25%, transparent 25%) 0 0 / 24px 24px, linear-gradient(135deg, transparent 75%, rgba(59, 126, 161, 0.18) 75%) 0 0 / 24px 24px, rgb(37 36 34); }
  .case-cover span { font-family: "JetBrains Mono", monospace; color: rgb(74 74 74); font-size: 0.75rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; }
  :global(.dark) .case-cover span { color: rgb(184 180 172); }
</style>
